# Testing Conventions

## Unit Tests (Vitest + React Testing Library)

Every component MUST have a co-located `Name.test.tsx`.

### Structure

```tsx
import { render, screen, fireEvent, cleanup } from "@testing-library/react";
import { describe, it, expect, vi, afterEach } from "vitest";
import { Button } from "./Button";

afterEach(cleanup);

describe("Button", () => {
  it("renders with text", () => {
    render(<Button>Click me</Button>);
    expect(screen.getByRole("button", { name: "Click me" })).toBeInTheDocument();
  });

  it("handles click events", () => {
    const onClick = vi.fn();
    render(<Button onClick={onClick}>Click me</Button>);
    fireEvent.click(screen.getByRole("button"));
    expect(onClick).toHaveBeenCalledOnce();
  });
});
```

### Rules

- Import `cleanup` and call `afterEach(cleanup)` at the top level of every test file.
- Use `screen` queries — prefer `getByRole`, `getByText`, `getByAltText` over `getByTestId`.
- Use `vi.fn()` for mocks, `vi.mock()` for module mocks.
- Test all variants/sizes with a loop: `variants.forEach(v => { const { unmount } = render(...); unmount(); })`.
- Test interactive behavior (clicks, disabled state, loading state).
- Test accessibility: check `aria-*` attributes, `disabled`, roles.

### What to Test per Layer

| Layer | Test focus |
|-------|-----------|
| Atoms | Renders, props, variants, sizes, disabled, events, a11y |
| Molecules | Renders children, composition, links/hrefs |
| Organisms | Section renders, all content visible, correct structure |
| Templates | Renders children, includes expected sub-components |

## Hook Tests

Controller hooks and utility hooks get their own test files in `src/hooks/`.

### Controller Hook Test Pattern

```tsx
import { renderHook, act } from "@testing-library/react";
import { describe, it, expect, vi, beforeEach } from "vitest";
import { useProjectList } from "./useProjectList";

vi.mock("@/actions/projects", () => ({
  deleteProject: vi.fn().mockResolvedValue({ error: null }),
}));

describe("useProjectList", () => {
  const initialProjects = [
    { id: "1", name: "Project A" },
    { id: "2", name: "Project B" },
  ];

  it("initializes with provided projects", () => {
    const { result } = renderHook(() => useProjectList(initialProjects));
    expect(result.current.projects).toHaveLength(2);
  });

  it("removes project on delete", async () => {
    const { result } = renderHook(() => useProjectList(initialProjects));
    await act(() => result.current.onDelete("1"));
    expect(result.current.projects).toHaveLength(1);
  });
});
```

### Key rules for hook tests

- Mock server actions with `vi.mock()` — hooks call server actions, never Supabase.
- Use `renderHook` from `@testing-library/react`.
- Wrap state-changing calls in `act()`.
- Test loading states, error states, and optimistic updates.
- Test that the correct server action is called with expected arguments.

## Server Action Tests

Server actions get co-located test files (e.g., `actions.test.ts` next to `actions.ts`).

### Server Action Test Pattern

```ts
import { describe, it, expect, vi, beforeEach } from "vitest";

vi.mock("@/lib/supabase/server", () => ({
  createClient: vi.fn(),
}));

import { createClient } from "@/lib/supabase/server";
import { createProject } from "./actions";

describe("createProject", () => {
  const mockSupabase = {
    auth: { getUser: vi.fn() },
    from: vi.fn().mockReturnThis(),
    insert: vi.fn().mockReturnThis(),
    select: vi.fn().mockReturnThis(),
    single: vi.fn(),
  };

  beforeEach(() => {
    vi.mocked(createClient).mockResolvedValue(mockSupabase as any);
    mockSupabase.auth.getUser.mockResolvedValue({
      data: { user: { id: "user-1" } },
    });
  });

  it("creates a project for authenticated user", async () => {
    mockSupabase.single.mockResolvedValue({ data: { id: "p-1", name: "Test" }, error: null });
    const result = await createProject("Test");
    expect(result.data).toEqual({ id: "p-1", name: "Test" });
    expect(result.error).toBeNull();
  });

  it("returns error when not authenticated", async () => {
    mockSupabase.auth.getUser.mockResolvedValue({ data: { user: null } });
    const result = await createProject("Test");
    expect(result.error).toBe("Not authenticated");
  });
});
```

### Key rules for server action tests

- Mock `@/lib/supabase/server` — never hit a real database.
- Test authentication checks (unauthenticated → error).
- Test validation failures.
- Test Supabase error propagation.
- Test the happy path returns expected shape.

## E2E Tests (Playwright)

Located in `apps/web/e2e/`. Named `feature.spec.ts`.

```ts
import { test, expect } from "@playwright/test";

test("homepage loads successfully", async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto("/");
  await expect(page).toHaveTitle(/SynthPress/i);
});

test("navbar has Sign Up link", async ({ page }) => {
  await page.goto("/");
  const signUpLink = page.getByRole("link", { name: "Sign Up" });
  await expect(signUpLink).toBeVisible();
  await expect(signUpLink).toHaveAttribute("href", "/signup");
});
```

### Rules

- Use `page.getByRole()`, `page.getByText()`, `page.locator()` — prefer semantic selectors.
- Each test navigates with `page.goto()` independently.
- Assert visibility with `toBeVisible()`, content with `toContainText()`, attributes with `toHaveAttribute()`.
- Test critical user flows: auth, CRUD operations, navigation guards.

## Coverage

Coverage thresholds are **100%** for statements, branches, functions, and lines across:
`src/components/`, `src/lib/`, `src/hooks/`, `src/services/`, `src/connectors/`, `src/stores/`, `src/actions/`.

Excluded from coverage: test files, story files, barrel `index.ts` files, `src/test/` setup, `src/types/`, and generated files like `database.types.ts`.
